1 The Big (Bayesian) Picture

How can we live if we dont change?
Beyonce. Lyric from Satellites.

Mind changes. There had to be some preconceptions about this book: preformed notions about this book even prior to opening this book, from its title, its online review, or from a conversation with a friend. Then, with this book starting with a quote by Beyonce, I probably changed my mind about this book quickly.

  • Wow, this book is going to be more fun than I even expected. or
  • Hmm, I dont know.

Changing is simply part of life.

We continuously update our knowledge about the world as we accumulate lived experiences, or collect data. Life is about collecting data and changing opinions.

Italian restaurant example:

  1. 5-star online rating & You love Italian food. Expectation: It will be quite good!

  2. 1st visit: Soggy mess. Adjusting the 5-star to 3-star personal rating.

  3. 2nd visit: Pleased with Alfredo. Increase the personal rating to 4 stars.

  4. Continued visits (Collect more and more edible data and update your knowledge each time.)

Figure 1.1: Your evolving knowledge about a restaurant.

Figure 1.1 captures the natural Bayesian knowledge-building process of acknowledging your preconceptions, using data to update your knowledge, and repeating. Such Bayesian approach can be applied to rigorous scientific research inquiries. You walk into such an inquiry with a context - you carry a degree of incoming or prior information based on previous research and experience. Naturally, its in light of this information that you interpret new data, weighing both in developing your updated or posterior information. You continue to refine this information as you gather new evidence (Figure 1.2).

Figure 1.2: A Bayesian knowledge-building diagram.

The Bayesian philosophy represented in Figure 1.2 is the foundation of Bayesian statistics.

Throughout this book, you will build the methodology and tools you need to implement this philosophy in a rigorous data analysis.

Goals

  • Learn to think like a Bayesian.

  • Explore the foundations of a Bayesian data analysis and how they contrast with the frequentist alternative.

  • Learn a little bit about the history of the Bayesian philosophy.

1.1 Thinking like a Bayesian

Bayesian approach is natural to knowledge building. Frequentist philosophy has traditionally dominated statistics, though. Although the distinction is sometimes hard to make in practice, and not one particular approach is used all the time, there is a need to illustrate the key differences between the logic behind the interpretation of Bayesian and frequentist analyses.

1.1.1 Quiz yourself

Take a quick quiz to assess your current inclinations. Just go with your gut.

  1. When flipping a fair coin, we say that the probability of flipping Heads is 0.5. How do you interpret this probability?

a) If I flip this coin over and over, roughly 50% will be Heads.

b) Heads and Tails are equally plausible.

c) Both a and b make sense.

  1. An election is coming up and a pollster claims that candidate A has a 0.9 probability of winning. How do you interpret this probability?

a) If we observe the election over and over, candidate A will win roughly 90% of the time.

b) Candidate A is much more likely to win than lose.

c) The pollsters calculation is wrong. Candidate A will either win or lose, thus their probability of winning can only be 0 or 1.

  1. Consider two claims. (1) Zuofu claims that he can predict the outcome of a coin flip. To test his claim, you flip a fair coin 10 times and he correctly predicts all 10. (2) Kavya claims that she can distinguish natural and artificial sweeteners. To test her claim, you give her 10 sweetener samples and she correctly identifies each. In light of these experiments, what do you conclude?

a) Youre more confident in Kavyas claim than Zuofus claim.

b) The evidence supporting Zuofus claim is just as strong as the evidence supporting Kavyas claim.

  1. Suppose that during a recent doctors visit, you tested positive for a very rare disease. If you only get to ask the doctor one question, which would it be?

a) Whats the chance that I actually have the disease?

b) If in fact I dont have the disease, whats the chance that I wouldve gotten this positive test result?

Tally up your quiz score using the system below.

Problem 1. a = +1, b = +3, c = +2

Problem 2. a = +1, b = +3, c = +1

Problem 3. a = +3, b = +1

Problem 4. a = +3, b = +1

2+3+3+1 = 9

Totals from 9-12 indicate alignment with the Bayesian philosophy. Totals from 4-5 indicate that your current thinking is fairly frequentist.

6-8 means youre in between, seeing the strength from both sides.

1.1.2 The meaning of probability

Probability theory is central to statistical analysis, but Bayesians and frequentists differ on the very definition of probability, just as illustrated by questions 1 and 2 in Section 1.1.1. Its the interpretation that differs.

Interpreting probability

  • In the Bayesian philosophy, a probability measures the relative plausibility of an event.

  • The frequentist philosophy is so named for its interpretation of probability as the long-run relative frequency of a repeatable event.

Therefore, a Bayesian would say that Heads and Tails are equally likely and frequentist would say that if we flip the coin over and over and over again, roughly 1/2 of these flips will be Heads.

But, in an election example where a pollster claims that candidate A has a 0.9 probability of winning the upcoming election, the election is a one-time event and the long-run relative frequency concept of observing the election over and over is simply inapplicable. This shows the cracks within the frequentist interpretation. A strict frequentist would say that the pollster is wrong. A less extreme frequentist interpretation would say that in long-run hypothetical repetitions of the election, i.e., elections with similar circumstances, candidate A would win roughly 90% of the time, however awkward this may sound.

The election example is not rare: an event of interest is unrepeatable.

  • Whether or not a potician wins an election,

  • Whether or not it rains tomorrow,

  • Whether or not humans will live on Mars one day, etc.

All of the above are one-time events.

Bayesian interpretation provides an alternative path by which to express the uncertainty of these events. A Bayesian for example would interpret a 0.9 probability of winning to mean that the relative plausibility of winning is high - the candidate is 9 times more likely to win than lose.

1.1.3 The Bayesian balancing act

Question 3 in Section 1.1.1 presented you with two scenarios (inspired by an example by Berger (1984)): (1) Zuofu claims that he can predict the outcomes of a coin flip and (2) Kavya claims that she can distinguish between natural and artificial sweeteners. Lets agree here that Zuofus claim is absurd and Kavyas claim is somewhat reasonable.

  • In frequentist view, the 10 out of 10 score by Zuofu and Kavya are the same, regardless of the context, or consideration of our prior contextual understanding. Frequentist view throws out all prior knowledge in favor of a mere 10 data points. We can represent the knowledge-building diagram of frequentist view with Figure (fig:frequentist-knowledge-building-diagram), which solely consists of the data.

Figure 1.3: A frequentist knowledge-building diagram.

  • In contrast, a Bayesian analysis gives voice to our prior knowledge.

    • Weighing their equivalent 10 out of 10 achievements against these different priors, our posterior understanding of Zuofus and Kavyas claims differ.

    • Bayesian allows ones prior experience to play a formal role in a statistical analysis.

    • Critique: It all seems too subjective not much work to combat this critique.

    • Combine your prior with some data and hocus pocus, poof, out pops your posterior.

    • Nope. Not at all like that in reality. The Bayesian philosophy provides a formal framework for such knowledge creation.

      • Prior information \(\stackrel{\mathrm{balance}{\longleftrightarrow}\) data

What does the balance between prior (information) and data mean? Its the relative strength of each.

Figure 1.4: Bayesian analyses balance our prior experiences with new data. Depending on the setting, the prior is given more weight than the data (left), the prior and data are given equal weight (middle), or the prior is given less weight than the data (right).

  • e.g.) We have a strong prior understanding that Zuofu is probably not likely to be a psychic, yet have very little data points (10 coin flips). Leftmost plot of Figure 1.4.

  • e.g.) But if Zuofu had correctly predicted the outcome of like 10,000 coin flips, the strength of the data would far surpass that of our prior, leading to a posterior conclusion that perhaps Zuofu IS psychic after all (like the right plot in Figure 1.4).

  • Allowing the posterior to balance out the prior and data is critical to the Bayesian knowledge-building process.

    • Little data Our posterior can draw upon the power in our prior knowledge.
    • Collection of more data The prior loses its influence.

This is natural in how people think. (In science, policy-making, and life overall.)

These two scientists will come to an agreement on the human role in climate change as data is being collected, no matter their prior training and experience. Two-person Bayesian knowledge-building process will result in a consensus of posterior (our posterior), as illustrated in Figure 1.5.1

Figure 1.5: A two-person Bayesian knowledge-building diagram.

1.1.4 Asking questions

In question 4 of Section 1.1.1, you were asked what if you tested positive for a rare disease, what would you ask?: (a) whats the chance that I actually have the disease?, or (b) whats the chance that I wouldve gotten this positive result if Im actually negative?

  • Bayesian analysis: Assessment of uncertainty of the hypothesis in light of the observed data
    • Bayesian hypothesis: In light of the observed data, whats the chance that the hypothesis is correct?
  • Frequentist analysis: Assessment of uncertainty of the observed data in light of an assumed hypothesis.
    • Frequentist hypothesis: If in fact the hypothesis is incorrect, whats the chance Id have observed this, or even more extreme data?

Consider this scenario in Table 1.1.

Table 1.1: Disease status and test outcomes for 100 people.
test positive test negative total
disease 3 1 4
no disease 9 87 96
total 12 88 100

In a population of 100, only four people have the disease. Among the 96 without the disease, nine test positive and thus get misleading test results. Among the four with the disease, three test positive and thus get accurate test results.

Bayesian would ask Given my positive test result, whats the chance that I actually have the disease? Given the data, whats the uncertainty in my hypothesis? Given the data points observed, how much would they explain my hypothesis?

  • Only 3 of the 12 people that tested positive have the actual disease.

Frequentist would ask If I dont actually have the disease, whats the chance that I wouldve tested positive? Whats the chance I would have gotten this positive result if Im not really positive? If the hypothesis is wrong in the first place, whats the chance I observe these data points?

  • Only 9 people out of the total of 96 people who are actually negative will test positive.

9/96 frequentist probability calculation is similar in spirit to a p-value. (Chance of having observed data that are as or more extreme than ours if in fact our original hypothesis is incorrect.)

P-value is fading in importance because it is commonly being misinterpreted. (ASA public safety announcement)

Its only natural to study the undertainty of a yet-unproven hypothesis (whether one has a rare disease), rather than the uncertainty of the data we have already observed (whether you incorrectly tested positive for the rare disease).

1.2 A quick history lesson

Bayesian rose to popularity recently. - Reverend Thomas Bayes - a statistician, minister, and philosopher (18th century) - Month Hall probability puzzle: Marilyn vos Savant came up with her Bayesian solution and was ridiculed by the readers. - Alan Turings cracking of Germanys Enigma code used Bayesian methods. - John Tukey pioneered election-day predictions using Bayesian methods.

Why now?

\(1\) Advances in computing - Bayesian applications require sophisticated computing resources that werent broadly available until the 1990s.

\(2\) Departure from tradition - People are departing from long-ingrained tradition.

\(3\) Reevaluation of subjectivity - Subjective is no longer a dirty word.

1.3 A look ahead

Common thread throughout the book: building and analyzing Bayesian models for the behavior of some variable \(Y\).

1.3.1 Unit 1: Bayesian foundations

Motivating question

How can we incorporate Bayesian thinking into a formal model of some variable of interest, \(Y\)?

Unit 1 give us the foundations of Bayesian analysis.

  • Bayes Rule

  • Build a few introductory but fundamental Bayesian models.

  • These unique models are tied together in the broader conjugate family.

  • Apply our Bayesian thinking with models tailored toward variables \(Y\) of differing structures.

  • e.g.) Beta-binomial model: Determine the probability that it rains tomorrow in Australia using data on binary categorical variable \(Y\), whether or not it rains for each of the 1000 sampled days. (Figure 1.7 (a))

  • e.g.) Gamma-Poisson model: Explore the rate of bald eagle sightings in Ontario, Canada using data on variable \(Y\), the counts of eagles seen in each of 37 one-week observation periods. (Figure 1.7 (b))

  • e.g.) Normal-Normal model: 3 p.m. temperature in Australia using data on the bell-shaped variable \(Y\), temperatures on a sample of study days. (Figure 1.7 (c))2

Figure 1.7: (a) Binomial output for the rain status of 1000 sampled days in Australia; (b) Poisson counts of bald eagles observed in 37 one-week observation periods; (c) Normally distributred 3 p.m. temperatures (in degrees Celsius) on 200 days in Australia.

1.3.2 Unit 2: Posterior simulation & analysis

Motivating questions

When our Bayesian models of \(Y\) become too complicated to mathematically \(specify\), how can we approximate them? And once weve either specified or approximated a model, how can we make meaning of and draw formal conclusions from it?

This part is concerned about the model approximation problem. What if we cant generalize our basic models we learned in Unit 1? We might not be able to actually specify the model. When we cant know something, we approximate it. We learn Markov chain Monte Carlo simulation techniques to approximate otherwise out-of-reach Bayesian models.

After specifying or approximating a Bayesian model, we must also be able to make meaning of and draw formal conclusions from the results. Posterior analysis is the process of asking what does this all mean?! and involves three major elements:

  • posterior estimation
  • hypothesis testing
  • prediction

1.3.3 Unit 3: Bayesian regression & classification

Motivating question

Were not always interested in the lone behavior of variable \(Y\). We may want to understand the relationship between a set of \(p\) potential predictor variables (\(X_1, X_2, \dots, X_p\)) and \(Y\). How do we build a Bayesian model of this relationship? And how do we know whether ours is a good model?

Before Unit 3, we were only interested in a single variable \(Y\). Once we have a grip on the response variable \(Y\), we have a follow-up question: Can we model and predict the response variable based on predictors? For example, can we predict 3 p.m temperatures in Australia based on 9 a.m. tempearatures (\(X_1\)) and precise location (\(X_2\))?

Bayesian modeling tools:

  • Modeling and predicting a quantitative response variable \(Y\) = regression task
  • Modeling and predicting a categorical response variable \(Y\) = classification task

Figure 1.8: (a) Tomorrows rain vs.todays humidity: classification problem; (b) the number of bald eagles over time: Poisson regression model problem of bald eagle counts increasing over time; (c) 3 p.m. vs 9 a.m. temperatures in two different Australian cities: Normal regression model problem between \(Y\) and predictors \(X_1\) and \(X_2\).

We explore two approaches of classification here: (1) logistic regression (extension of the Unit 1 Beta-Binomial model) and (2) Naive Bayes classification (simplified extension of Bayes Rule).

1.3.4 Unit 4: Hierarchical Bayesian models

Motivating question

What if the structure of our data violates the independence assumptions behind the Unit 3 regression and classification models? Specifically, suppose we have multiple observations per random group in our dataset. How do we tweak our Bayesian models to not only acknowledge, but harness the structure?

Assumptions of independence: our data on the response and predictor variables \((Y,X_1,X_2, \dots , X_p)\) is a random sample.

observation y x
1
2
3

We expand the flexibility of our Bayesian modeling by accommodating hierarchical, or grouped data.

group y x
A
A
B
B
B

These are called the hierarchical models. We can appropriately reflect this data structure in our models to avoid doing the wrong thing, but also increase the power to detect the underlying trends in the relationships between \(Y\) and \((X_1, X_2, \dots, X_p)\).

1.4 Chapter summary

We learned how to think like a Bayesian in Chapter 1.

Fundamental Bayesian knowledge-building process (Figure 1.2):

  • Construct our posterior knowledge by balancing information from our data with our prior knowledge.
  • As more and more data come in, we continue to refine this knowledge, which will fade the influence of original prior into the background.
  • As more and more and data come in, two analysts that start out with opposing knowledge will eventually converge on the same posterior knowledge.
